# Plans

A **plan** says *how* to deliver one milestone. Milestones say *what*
and *why*; plans decompose the work into PR-sized tasks, resolve the
milestone's open questions, annotate every task with the right kind of
AI agent, and lay out which tasks can run in parallel.

Canonical template: [`docs/roadmaps/PLAN_TEMPLATE.md`](../../docs/roadmaps/PLAN_TEMPLATE.md).
Copy it; don't reinvent the structure.

## Where plans live

```
docs/roadmaps/<YYYY-MM-DD> <roadmap-name>/plans/<YYYY-MM-DD> <plan-name>.md
```

Plans are **dated** so multiple plans against the same milestone (e.g.
when an approach gets replaced mid-stream) coexist as historical
record. Old plans stay; new plans link back.

## Required sections

In order, every plan has:

1. **Header** — created date, author, milestone link, status, total effort.
2. **Summary** — 1–2 sentences.
3. **Open questions resolved** — every open question from the milestone,
   with the decision in **bold** plus a one-sentence rationale.
4. **Out of scope** — what this plan defers.
5. **Tasks** — each one PR-sized.
6. **Wave plan** — explicit parallelization.
7. **Risks and rollback**.
8. **Definition of Done (this plan)**.
9. **Notes** — dated scratchpad.

## Task fields (all required)

| Field | Notes |
|---|---|
| **ID** | `T01`, `T02`, … unique within the plan |
| **Title** | Imperative, fits in one line |
| **Depends on** | Other task IDs, or `—` if none |
| **Wave** | Integer; tasks in the same wave run in parallel |
| **Agent** | See "Agent selection" below |
| **Effort** | `XS` (~30 min), `S` (~2 h), `M` (~half day), `L` (~full day or split) |
| **Files** | List the files the PR is expected to touch |
| **PR title** | Drafted up front in Conventional Commits format |
| **Acceptance** | Specific behaviors / tests that must pass |

If a task feels bigger than `L`, **split it** before starting.

## Parallelization

The Wave plan is the actionable part. Tasks in the same wave have
*no* shared dependencies and can be picked up by separate agents (or
in separate worktrees) simultaneously.

A simple invariant before starting a wave: **every task in the wave
has all its `Depends on` items already merged to `main`**.

```
Wave 1   T01                 foundational, no parallel work
Wave 2   T02                 unblocks the next wave
Wave 3   T03  ‖  T04         both depend only on T02
Wave 4   T05                 integration step
```

When two tasks in the same wave touch the same file, either move one
to the next wave or split the file into independent pieces first.

## Agent selection

Pick the lowest-cost agent that can do the task reliably. The point
isn't to minimize cost — it's to reserve high-reasoning capacity for
work that actually needs it.

| Agent class | Best for | Concrete examples (substitute what you have) |
|---|---|---|
| **Fast / cheap** | Mechanical edits, formatting, doc tweaks, find-and-replace, trivial type additions | `composer-2-fast`, `kimi-k2.5` |
| **Default workhorse** | Typical feature implementation with tests, normal refactors | `claude-4.6-sonnet-medium-thinking` |
| **High-reasoning** | Architectural decisions, hard debugging, layered refactors, novel algorithms | `claude-opus-4-7-thinking-xhigh`, `gpt-5.3-codex` |
| **Read-only `explore` subagent** | "Survey how X is used", "find all places that mutate Y" — exploration that informs but doesn't write code | Spawn before writing the plan; results inform task decomposition |
| **`generalPurpose` subagent** | Multi-step research that mixes exploration with edits | Use sparingly; usually a focused single-agent run is cleaner |
| **`best-of-n-runner`** | When multiple algorithm choices are plausible and a small benchmark or comparison would settle it | Try 2–3 implementations of `relaxOverlaps` in parallel worktrees, compare outputs |
| **`shell` subagent** | Long shell-heavy sessions: complex git ops, bulk renames, dependency upgrades | Branch surgery, `rg`-driven mass edits |

Decision tree:

```
Is the task > 80% mechanical (rename, format, copy-paste a pattern)?
  yes → fast/cheap
Is the task an architectural decision or genuinely tricky?
  yes → high-reasoning
Are we trying to compare approaches?
  yes → best-of-n-runner
Otherwise → default workhorse
```

Annotate the model used in the **PR description** so future plans
can recalibrate ("we said sonnet for T02, but it needed three
revisions — bump to opus next time").

## Authoring checklist

When writing a plan from scratch:

1. Read the milestone doc end-to-end. Copy its open-questions list.
2. Resolve every open question. Decisions go in **bold**.
3. List explicit out-of-scope items to head off scope creep.
4. Decompose into tasks. One PR each. Use the table format.
5. For each task, fill **all** fields. If you can't write the
   acceptance criteria yet, the task isn't ready — split or research.
6. Build the Wave plan. Verify no two same-wave tasks touch the same
   file.
7. Sanity check: the union of "Files" across tasks covers everything
   the milestone needs to change.
8. Add risks/rollback. At minimum: what happens if the foundational
   task (T02-equivalent) ends up wrong?
9. Set status to `draft`. Open a PR for the plan itself before
   starting code work — that PR's diff is the plan content, and
   reviewers can challenge decisions before any task starts.

## Executing a plan

1. Set status to `executing` when wave 1 starts.
2. Open one PR per task. PR title = the task's `PR title` field. PR
   body links the task ID and milestone.
3. As tasks merge, update the plan's task list with a ✓ or strike-through
   so anyone glancing at the plan sees progress at a glance.
4. If a task discovers a missed dependency or design issue, update the
   plan in the same PR (or a small follow-up commit). Don't let the
   plan diverge from reality.
5. When the last task lands, update milestone status in the roadmap and
   set this plan's status to `done`.

## When the model is asked to "write a plan"

If the user says something like *"write a plan for milestone 01"* or
*"plan the next milestone"*:

1. Read the relevant milestone doc.
2. Read this rule and `PLAN_TEMPLATE.md`.
3. Copy the template to
   `docs/roadmaps/<active roadmap>/plans/<today> <slug>.md`.
4. Fill it in. Resolve open questions; if a question genuinely needs
   user input, **leave it blank with a `❓ ASK USER:` marker** and
   surface it in the chat reply rather than guessing.
5. Run `pnpm --filter mind-map-sv lint` (markdown is in scope of
   prettier on the root install) — the plan should pass formatting.
6. Open the plan for review before starting any code work.
